hands_on_practices.problem:
A particle of mass $m$ is confined to a one-dimensional box of length $L$. The potential energy $V(x)$ is zero for $0 \le x \le L$ and infinite elsewhere. The stationary states of this system have quantized energy levels given by $E_n = \frac{n^2 \pi^2 \hbar^2}{2mL^2}$, where $n$ is a positive integer and $\hbar$ is the reduced Planck constant.

At time $t=0$, the particle is prepared in a state described by the following normalized trial wavefunction, $\Psi(x)$:
$$
\Psi(x) = \begin{cases}
\sqrt{\frac{12}{L^3}} x & \text{for } 0 \le x \le L/2 \\
\sqrt{\frac{12}{L^3}} (L-x) & \text{for } L/2 < x \le L \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$
If a measurement of the particle's total energy is performed on this state, what is the probability that the measurement will yield the ground state energy, $E_1$? Your answer should be a dimensionless, analytic expression.
